Nagara


The ながら grammar pattern is used to express "while doing something" or "simultaneously doing two actions". It connects two actions that are happening at the same time, with the main action being emphasized and the secondary action being described with ながら.

Formation of ながら
Take the ます stem of a verb (the verb without the ます ending).
Add ながら to it.
The main action (the one you want to emphasize) comes after the ながら clause.
Example:
食べる (to eat) → 食べながら (while eating)
聞く (to listen) → 聞きながら (while listening)
Key Points
ながら is used when two actions are performed at the same time.

The action after ながら is the secondary action (less important).
The action in the main clause is the primary action (more important).
Both actions must be performed by the same subject.

The verb before ながら is always in its ます stem form.

10 Examples of ながら
音楽を聞きながら、勉強します。
(I study while listening to music.)

聞く (to listen) → 聞きながら
Main action: 勉強します (study)
Secondary action: 音楽を聞きます (listen to music)
テレビを見ながら、ご飯を食べます。
(I eat while watching TV.)

見る (to watch) → 見ながら
Main action: ご飯を食べます (eat)
Secondary action: テレビを見ます (watch TV)
歩きながら、電話をします。
(I talk on the phone while walking.)

歩く (to walk) → 歩きながら
Main action: 電話をします (talk on the phone)
Secondary action: 歩きます (walk)
歌を歌いながら、シャワーを浴びます。
(I take a shower while singing a song.)

歌う (to sing) → 歌いながら
Main action: シャワーを浴びます (take a shower)
Secondary action: 歌を歌います (sing a song)
本を読みながら、コーヒーを飲みます。
(I drink coffee while reading a book.)

読む (to read) → 読みながら
Main action: コーヒーを飲みます (drink coffee)
Secondary action: 本を読みます (read a book)
友達と話しながら、歩きます。
(I walk while talking with my friend.)

話す (to talk) → 話しながら
Main action: 歩きます (walk)
Secondary action: 友達と話します (talk with a friend)
音楽を聞きながら、料理をします。
(I cook while listening to music.)

聞く (to listen) → 聞きながら
Main action: 料理をします (cook)
Secondary action: 音楽を聞きます (listen to music)
スマホを見ながら、電車に乗ります。
(I ride the train while looking at my smartphone.)

見る (to look) → 見ながら
Main action: 電車に乗ります (ride the train)
Secondary action: スマホを見ます (look at my smartphone)
ゲームをしながら、ジュースを飲みます。
(I drink juice while playing a game.)

する (to do) → しながら
Main action: ジュースを飲みます (drink juice)
Secondary action: ゲームをします (play a game)
音楽を聞きながら、宿題をします。
(I do my homework while listening to music.)

聞く (to listen) → 聞きながら
Main action: 宿題をします (do homework)
Secondary action: 音楽を聞きます (listen to music)
Common Mistakes
ながら cannot be used if the two actions are performed by different subjects.

Incorrect: 母が料理をしながら、私はテレビを見ます。
(This is incorrect because the subject changes from "mother" to "I.")
Correct: 母が料理をしている間に、私はテレビを見ます。
(While my mother is cooking, I watch TV.)
The action before ながら must be in the ます stem form, not the dictionary form.

Incorrect: 歩くながら、電話をします。
Correct: 歩きながら、電話をします。
Practice Sentences
Try creating your own sentences using ながら! Here are some ideas to get you started:

What do you do while listening to music?
Example: 音楽を聞きながら、何をしますか？
(What do you do while listening to music?)

What do you do while eating?
Example: ご飯を食べながら、何をしますか？
(What do you do while eating?)

By practicing ながら, you'll be able to describe simultaneous actions in Japanese fluently!